            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-10-17T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-10-17T14:00:00-05:00" n="1022" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1022">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860h.00/10–1745: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gallman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-10-17T19:00:00+00:00">October 17, 1945—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 17—6:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10877. British Ambassador to Belgrade who is in London today remarked to Foreign
                    Office official that in his opinion although Moscow would not always back Tito
                    to the hilt it would not take any action which would jeopardize the position of
                    Communist Party in Yugo. Stevenson therefore did not believe that Soviets would
                    ever associate themselves with any representations to Tito regarding internal
                    structure of Yugo or suggestions regarding elections.</p>
                <p>Sent to Department as 10877; repeated to Belgrade as 31.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gallman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
